This not only confirms that some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory already widely spread, but also provides more details than the fossils, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
According to scientists, the plumage of this animal was brown chestnut on the upper part, with a pale or carotenoid coloring on the lower part.
The discovery also allows to obtain detailed information about the evolution of birds' feathers.
Since the dinosaur's plumage is not equipped with the basic structure, the so-called rachis, but instead has other characteristics typical of feathers, such as barbs and barbules, researchers have concluded that the rachis is probably the result of an evolutionary development subsequent to these characteristics.
The structure of the plumage suggests that it was not used for flight, but rather for temperature regulation or courtship. Researchers hypothesize that, although it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the specimen shows adult plumage and not down feathers typical of a chick.
According to the researchers' hypotheses, despite the tail belonging to a young dinosaur, the sample reveals feathering typical of an adult specimen and not that of a chick.
